{
  "text": "In S. pneumoniae, the pyruvate oxidase gene (spxB) produces H 2 O 2 via pyruvate metabolism [CITATION_1] . We constructed an spxB mutant S. pneumoniae serotype 4 by introducing a kanamycinresistance gene into the spxB gene of bacteria. As expected, H 2 O 2 produced by spxB mutant bacteria was negligible (Fig. 6C) . Further, we found that knocking out spxB eliminates the vast majority of the DNA-damaging potential of serotype 4 (Fig. 6D) . These results show a direct correlation between S. pneumoniae's genotoxicity and its ability to produce H 2 O 2 .",
